{"/service/ndnp/vi/batch_vi_mustang_ver01/data/sn90052005/0039334975A/1914010101/0013.xml":{"full_text":"JANUARY 1\nFULL, FAIR, CLEAN AND ACCURATE,\nisvery Moraine In the T\u00abur.\nBy\nJUCHMOVD VIRGINIAN COMPANY,\nIncorporated.\nMcBONALO u:p PVr*t<1cnt.\nR. WOODFIN, tieneral Manaff\nB. WIUAAMS. <\u2019ontrlhnHne Edltor.\nVIRGINIAN BITT.PINO,\nFranklin Streets.\nRichmond, Virginia.\nBy Mail, Postage Raid.\nOn? Si* Three\nTear. Mob. Mob.\nwith Sunday I'.OP j:.f>0 Ji 25\nwithout Sunday... do I no 1 oo\nonly 2.00 1 00 .SO\nOne\nMo.\n.50\n.35\n.25\nVirginian Carriers\u2019 Belivrrr Sorrier 1t> TUrh\nmomt (ami suburbs' uni? Petersburg\nJSg Weekly. By Month.\nRally with Sunday ifl I\nbaity without Sunday O', \u20222fi\nJttoday only.\u2014 .0^ 20\nRnterp 1 a\u00ab rr 1 -ela-t*e maMcr. Jn.ria.rT 23.\nli-tt the poetoffirr of Richmond, Va. under\nOf March 153T\nTHURSDAY, JANUARY 1, UH.\nWITH RACK TO Till FCTTRE.\nRlood and storm and fife and war did their\nRut to make the year 1013 one of horror. A\n(\u2022Altai change in government and in govern\nRMBtal policy, tariff reduction and the reorgani\nRUlon of our currency system, accompanied by\nRuilness depression. did its heat to make for\njpNBiicism in the industrial world and there\n|HK not larking those w ho w ere willing to give\nftt Hnpptus.\ntfho yeer was on\u00ae of catastrophe; it was onp\nRf war; it was one of business depression, and\nfBt with it all it was a year which marked an\nRjyance 'n 8\u2018' lines of endeavor. In science. In\n\u2022Udlcine, ir, business and in the njovement to\nqjpgA. world peace, in government and in progress\n(Uard better business conditions and greater\n\u2022OCiai justice much has been accomplished. Tha\n\u2022fj of the pessimist is unheeded and. exemplify\nRig; the growing faith of man In man and in\n|Rg Autiny of the race. It was not heeded greatly\nwhen the outlook was darkest. The war\nbut smoulder in the Balkans; they have\nbeen extinguished. In Mexico a battle Is\nat this moment and a tyrant dictator\nlOl holds the reins of government. But who\n\u2022(teres that great, strides have not been made\naward universal peace? Who doubts that\n(\u25a0BByaon\u2019s vision of the future Is not clearer\ntptfay than ever before?\nTtlie year bt^gan with business depression. The\nWilli ill redi^iftlon In the. tariff made even those*\nfw sympathy with the operation doubt Its first\n/$ut today business Is beginning to show\nImprovement. Th\" situation In Rich\nllpant l\u00ab typical. Bank clearings for the year\na decrease tinder 1912, but the decrease\nall during the first eight months of the year\nSeptember they began to grow and with\nmonth rose steadily until December when\nlargest clearings In the history of Richmond\nwere reported. In manufacturing there\n|S m decrease for the year, but during the last\nor four months operations were on a larger\nand many workmen who had been laid\n\u2022ff were able to secure work again. In Jobbing\nfl\u00abj> increase for the year was below the lncrense\nfor -1912. but here, too. It was the lean eight\n\u25a0Moths which accounts for it, the close of the\nyppr showing a resumption in trade. Postal re\nCatpts In Richmond In December w ore larger than\ntar any other December in the history of the\n.pastoffiee. So it is practically all over the coun\ntry. The.promise of disaster held out during\ntfc* arrester part of the year was not. fulfilled.\nHW*e skies are clearing and the outlook for 1911\n|p bright\nRichmond has grown and progressed during\nOta twelve months which ended yesterday. In\n\u25a0MBs lines the increase* were smaller than has\nfctan the case: In others there has been an actual\nflaerrnr but even berr comparison with other\npities of similar site give us cause for hope and\nPPOUdenre. The increased manufacturing output,\nput Increased Jobbing trade, the increased re\ntall trade, the Increased bank clearings\u2014all with\n|WO great governmental policies Intimately affect\ning business in the process of radical change\ngive promise of better things to rom\u00bb. Rooking\nback upon the last twelve months and especially\nMpon the concluding monthB of the year Rfoh\nOtond 1s encouraged and is prepared to face the\ncoming year with a confidence born of knowledge\n\u25a0C Richmond's advantages. >f Richmond\u2019s spirit,\npf Richmond\u2019s determination\nIf PKMOCRAT1ZK Tin: r\\IVFR.SITV.\nThe University of Virginia wag eonorlved 1n\nthe brain of Thomas Jefferson, born of hlg In\njjjfstll tih' I ff and started on Its ilfeV-jour\nGtr along tic linos laid out according to l.ia far\n\u2022tgbted vision. Under his eye It began lire, but\n\u2022nter the eare of oth\"rs it was not brought up\nIn the ideals of the Great Democrat and ha;\nI\u00abnrted therefrom Today we witness the\n^jppuaiy of a great Institution breathing the air\nIt Hontieello. revering the memory of Its sage.\n{Mating with pride to him as Its founder and\n|MUnr in his reflected glory, and yet with a\nand ideals not in amord with his\nala is proud of her university, of its past\nof its present. Virginia is proud of that\nIty's prestige which makes It tower abov.i\nwith better equipment, larger endowment\nlarger number of students. The name of\n,Cj\u00bbiveraity of Virginia is known wherever\n\u2022ante of Thomas Jefferson is known; wher\niht name of Virginia is known and the\n\u2022dories in it. Virginia is hopeful of the\nof her university, and is willing to b\u00ab\n(taxed that the future may brine those hopes to\nfruition.\nBut Virginia wants more than prestige. It\ni wants more than to attract audent* from all\nsections of the country. It wants more than\nj fame. It wants the use of its university. It\nwants the ideals of Tbomaa Jefferson restored.\nIt wants Its university democratized.\nMr. Jefferson Intended the University of Vir\nginia for the capstone of the State's public edu\ncation system. With that vision of the future\nwhich Is given to the few Immortals he aaw\nthe day when the public education system should\nbe the foundation stone of the State. He saw\nvisions of a child entering the primary school,\ngoing through the grammar school and the high\nschools and passing without pause into the Uni\nversity of Virginia, leaving equipped to fight the\nbuttles of life and to serve the State of Vlr\ngin la.\nBut it ha\u00bb %ot been so. There has been no\nconnecting link between the public schools of\nVirginia and Its university. The people have\nsuffered themselves to be taxed for the support\nof the University of Virginia ewea though de\nriving little material benefit from it. They have\nsupported It loyally and are prepared to con\ntlnue to support it They are prepared to do\nj more now than ever before because they are\nbeginning to take a more intimate interest In\nlit than ever before. They are beginning to\nrealize what the University of Virginia was In\ntended to be and to catch up with Mr. Jeffer\n5 son\u2019s ideas; to understand hie ideals; to see what\nhe saw a hundred years ago. They want and\nj will have more than a sentimental interest In\n[the school; they want it to be used for them\nj selves and for their children; they want it to\nbe a democratic institution.\nOne evidence of this change in sentiment to\nward the University of Virginia is tho strong\nsupport given the movement for a coordinate\n[college at Charlottesville. The education of the\n[women of Virginia is absolutely essential. Tha\nbest is absolutely essential and if that best can\nbe obtained nowhere save at the University of\n[Virginia at the University of Virginia It must\n(be obtained. Girls are admitted to our public\nschools and to our high sebools. If the Uni\nI verslty of Virginia is to be a State university,\nsupported by all the people of the State for all\ntho people of the State, and if the State has\nnot the money to establish a separate school tor\n\u25a0women, or if It can be established at less cost\nat Charlottesville, or If belter results can be\nobtained with a co-ordinate college at Charlottes\nville there is nothing more to be said. There is\nground for honest difference of opinion and for\nargument as to cost and results, but there is\nno room for prejudice. This is no time for\nj vague talk of the \u201cspirit\u201d of the University of\nVirginia, which, whatever it Is or whatever It Is\nnot, is not the spirit of Thomas Jefferson, tho\n(founder of the University of Virginia.\nLARGER POSTOFFIOE ST5EDED.\nThe Christmas holiday rush at the Richmond\npostofflc.e was not required to demonstrate to\nthose best informed of the pressing need of a\nI larger postofflce building for Richmond, but It\nemphasized the fact and brought home to many\npeople who were not acquainted with the In\nj terlor of the building and had no meana of know\ning of the crowded conditions,\nj Recently Richmond was a terminal station of\nthe railway postofflce. Little notice was given\nand it waa with difficulty that everything was\ngot Into working order In time, but It was done\nand on the opening day the Influx of parcel\npost matter teas handled as well as possible\ni under the adverse conditions. The lack of room\nconstituted those adverse conditions. In the mail\ning department the same condition prevailed and\nhas prevailed for some time. A building a year\nold Is now too small for the needs of Richmond.\nAll of this, of course, is a gratifying sign of\nRichmond's progress. It Is pleasing that busi\nness should have grown so rapidly as to mak\u00ab\na $800,000 building barely completed too small\nto handle the mall going through it. It is\ngratifying that the parcel post should havs\nproven such an unexpected success that accom\nmodations deemed more than sufficient should\nhave proven greatly deficient. But gratification\nat these evidences of the city's growth should\nprove an incentive toward work for the handling\nof an even larger amount of business. The\nrecommendation of Postmaster Edgar Allan that\nthe building be enlarged to cover the entire\nblock is a recommendation eminently wise, it\nshould be heeded by the government, and It is\npleasing to know that Congressman Montague\nand the Virginia senators realize Richmond's\nneeds and will do all within their power to see\nthat they are supplied.\nsrtXTEsa\n-Vh* Virginian la sure that It voices the sen\ntime-fit* of jits readers, whatever their religious\nfaith, whatever their denomination, when it ex\ntends heartiest congratulations to Richmond col\nlege. to its trustee* and president, and to all\nho have helped in the campaign for a fund\nwith which to extend the influence of the col\nlege\nIt Is sure that it voices the sentiments pf all\nits readers and it is sure that it arouses the\njealousy of none when it extends its heartiest\ncongratulations to President Boatwright and as\nsigns to him the chief credit for the successful\ntermination of the campalgQ.\nGreater Richmond college means a great deol\nto the Baptist denomination in Virginia and in\nthe South it means a great deal to the State\nand a great deal to Richmond- It means more\nto all, however, that a campaign to which all\ns ere pledged has ended is success. \"'The fight\nwas bard, the work difficult At times discour\nagement threatened the stoutest heart, but the\ncourage of the workers never failed. Working\nand fighting to the last they succeeded In their\npurpose to secure the half million needed to\ncomplete the work begun at Wtoatnampton. and\nnow the future of Greater Richmond college Is\nassured. The same work, the same fighting\nspirit the same faith put Into the conduct of\nthe school, will assure Its success as h great\ncollege for Christian education.\nPEOPLE\u2019S FORUM\nCard of Thanks.\nEditor of The Virginian:\nSir,\u2014Kindly allow me space In your colums\nto express my thanka to the many friends who\ngenerously came to my assistance In your re\ncent Christmas Gift Distribution.\nThe one hundred dollars, won as one of the\nprises, was duly sent to me by your buslnes*\nmanager, and has already found Us way. in ac\ncordance with my previously declared purpose.\nInto the building fund of our new Denny-Street\nMethodist church.\nVery truly yours.\nJ. W. EURE.\nT. H. Eliott.\nEditor of The Virginian:\nSir,\u2014In the death of Deacon T. H. Ellett. of\nRichmond, the State and city have both lost\na moBt valuable citizen, one ntho gave h!s\ntime and means to the uplift of his fellow\nmen in many ways. He was a noble, conse\ncrated Christina, devoted to the Baptist Church\nand all of Its benevolent causes. He was prob\niably the best friend the Baptist Orphanage had,\ni which seemed to lay heavily and lovingly on\nhis heart at all times. He was a friend which\nI admired, respected and loved; it was a real\npleasure to be In his presence and to hear\nand know of his devotion to the causes which\nstood for the best things In life.\nWo can 111 afford to lose such true and noble\nmen, but Ood in His providence and wisdom\nknows best, and we must be submissive and\nbow to His will.\nFew npen are willing to give both time and\nmoney to the service of the Lord as he did.\nj Clod grant that his life may be an Inspiration\nto many of us toward leading unselfish lives\nj of usefulness and Christian service,\nj R S. BARBOUR.\nSouth B*\u00abton, Va., Dec. 30.\nCURRENT COMMENT\nIn line for a Call Down.\n\"Who will be the next governor of South\nCarolina Is not. In itself, a matter of supreme\nImportance.\n\u201cThe question of capital importance Is what\nkind of a man for governor the people want.\n\"If the people wish to have an honest man\nfor governor, one who Is on the side of law and\ncivilization, who believes In equal justice to all\nmen. they will have him.\n\"But If the people wish to have the lawa set\nat naught, If they regard courts and juries as\npestiferous nuisances, 1f they consider the\nstatutes Imposing penalties for crimes as not\nto be taken seriously, they will be able to have\na governor who will carry out their bidding.\n\"The people can always get what they want.\nThey have the ballots.\"\u2014Columbia State.\nIf the editor of The State doesn't mind, he Is\ngoing to get a hard call from some of the folks\nin Carolina who do not look with favor upon\nfull penitentiaries and such things as interfere\nwith man\u2019s liberties.\u2014Savannah Press.\nNot too Old to be President.\nElthu Root says he must not be considered\nas a presidential posibility. He Is too oJd.\nIn 19X6 Mr. Root will be seventy-one. And\nseventy-one. as Mr. Root Interprets the Ameri\ncan standard, Is too old.\nIt Is not a fact that no American septuagena\nrian has been elected president. But that by no\nmeans proves that a septuagenarian Is Inca\npacitated by weight of years to carry the bur\nden of government.\nGladstone Is considered the greatest British\nstatesman of the last century. He was eighty\nthree when he formed his last cabinet, and for\nthe last time assumed the responsibility of rul\ning the British empire.\nBismarck was seventy-three when he finally\nresigned the chancellorship.\nTalleyrand at seventy-six was sttll the- lead\ning statesman of France.\nThiers was severity-four when he became first\npresident of the third French republic.\nMetternlch at seventy-five was Austria\u2019s\nprime minister, and the most astute statesman\nof Europe.\nThree score and ten may he. by the American\nstandard, an age too great for the responsi\nbilities of national leadership. But the history\nof the last 100 years shows that the standard\nis wrong.\nAny Intelligent reader of current history can\nthink of plenty of reasons why Mr. Root should\nnot, and could not, he elected president. But\nhis age is not one of them.\u2014Cleve'and Plain\nDealer.\nSecretary Bryan\u2019s Peary Tributes.\nHolland Is the first nation of Europe, but\nthe sixth In the total count to date, with which\nSecretary Bryan In the Ufrt four months has\nnegotiated a genera! peace and arbitration\ntreaty.\nIn thus setting an example to the great\npowers in the promotion of the world's peace,'\nthe 1\u2019nited States Is advancing their Interests\nas well as Its own. A step that makes more\nremote the poslbillty of International conflict,\nand leads to the amicable adjustment of dif\nferences in either hemisphere Is a victory for\nthe universal cause of civilization. Tt Is the\ndenial of the old rule that might makes right,\nfor which militarism still stands, and the af\nfirmation tHat reason and Justice shall prevail j\nwith the strong as well as the weak.\nBy creating permanent Impartial tribunals J\nto which appeal shall be made, the at^minls-\ntratlon plane to provide other means of reach\ning a solution w'hen the ordinary methods of\ndiplomacy fall of their purpose. The machinery\nwill always be ready for service in any emer\ngency The International tribunal will serve!\nas a court to investigate and report, but both j\nparties may act Independently as respects the\nmatter In dilute after the court's report la\nsubmitted.\nThe six Bryan arbitration treaties are but\nthe entering wedge. They relate only to minor\npower*. But they establish a principle of which\nno nation, no matter how well Armed or self-!\nconfident, can deny the Justice or dispute the\nforce except by discrediting its own good faith\nand honor a* an agency for peace.1\u2014New York\nWorld.\nHuerta\u2019s Successor*.\nIt is not too soon to talk of the successors of\nHusrtsu Even tho conservative Mexican sen\nHHkrftRhMA\nThe New Year of 1914\nIt Reminds Us of the Satisfactory\nResult of Keeping Faith With\nOurselves and You\nWhen, a little more than\ntwenty-eight years ago,\nin the little store at 117\nEast Broad Street, this\nvast business was begun\nand many of our present\nday accomplishments were\nbeing prepared for, one\nbasic principle was estab\n1 i s h e d\u2014T O K E E P\nFAITH.\nNotwithstanding the\nyear 1912 recorded the\nGREATEST VOLUME\nP OF BUSINESS ever done\n9 in the store\u2019s career, a\nreview of the nearly com\npleted business year of\n11913 tells ns that again\nprosperity has been with\nus and that records will be\nbroken.\nWe believed then, and it has been\nproved to ns since, that keeping\nfaith is the most valued jewel a mer\nchant can have. And never, know\ninglv, have we modified our first\nconception of what keeping faith\nmeans; with ns there can be no sub\nstatute.\nTo this, along with the right\nmerchandise, we quickly added\nCOURTESY, which was to be ap\nparent in all our transactions with\nmankind. Thus, almost before our\nbusiness actually started on its road\nof progress\u2014ENERGY and EN\nTHUSIASM became importantly\nhelpful factors.\nContinually, year after year,\nwithout undue acclaim or self-pro\njection, this business of ours and\nyours has PROSPERED\u2014it has\ngrown healthily and steadily in\nexact proportion to its endeavor.\nBy your INCREASING patron\nage, which is a splendid endorse\nment of both our merchandise and\nour methods of doing business, it\nlias been demonstrated that there is\nreal appreciation of a Department\nStore of the first class, and that the\nselling of goods of UNQUESTION\nABLE QUALITY at moderate\nprices is desired.\nSo we are again GRATEFUL\u2014\nfor is not appreciation a golden at\ntribute of life? Your FRIEND\nSHIP, gained only after you have\nmeasured our worth and tested\nour integrity, has made our store\nwhat it is today.\nWith deeply grateful hearts WE\nTHANK YOU, simply and sin\ncerely, renewing our pledges that\nare now over a quarter-century old,\nand wishing you\u2014\nA Prosperous and Happy New Year\nJanuary 1,1914. MILLER RHOADS.\ntiment 1* of the view that It would be too lati\nnow to irlve recognition to Huerta, as his day\nas dictator are numbered. It la only a matte1\nof time and method as to his exit from the atagi\nof political action.\nSetting him aside, there is a choice group o\nconstitutionalists to choose from. Heading it li\nCarranza, an old bandit, without any of th<\nbreadth or the vigor of Huerta, and who is onl;\ntitular head of the revolution. Then there ti\nBmlliano Zapata, the Attlla of the South, whi\nhas record of blood and pillage and ravishmen1\nthat would put to blush the chief of a Tarta;\nhorde. Then there Is Villa, who only needs tin\nextension of hla name by the rejection of an I\nand the ending of It with an X to properly de\nscribe him. Then there are Aguilar and Blanc'\nand half adrxetilewrarttghts who\nidentlal beacon blazing before them.\nIn adltlon to this select list of constitutions\nworthies, there remain de la Barra and Dia:\nand O-omez and other lights that failed. Thi\nprospect for peace and good order for Mexict\ncan hardly be said to be assured in the handi\nof any of this group\u2014and there are no othen\nof better caliber.\u2014Baltimore American.\nIn Wishing You a Very Happy and\nProsperous New Year\nThe American\nNational Bank\nof Richmond, Va.t\nwishes to extend to you something which\nwill help you realize this in the fullest de\ngree. If you start the year with the re\nsolve that your business shall prove more\nsatisfactory In every way, you cannot make\na mtstake If you select a strong, reliable\nbank as the channel through which to\nconduct your financial affairs. This insti\ntution guarantees unexcelled\nSECURITY AND SERVICE\nto all of its customera Come In and let\nus assist you In arranging your financial\naffairs satisfactorily.\nCapital'and Surplus .$1,600,000.00\nReaoaroea ..*6.600.000.00\nINCREASE LUMBER RATES\nTO VIRGINIA SHIPPERS\nr 1\nnterstate Commerce Commission Grants Application of the\nSouthern Railway. Rate on Logs Is Lowered by\nAnother Order of the Commission.\nWASHINGTON, Dec. 31.\u2014The in\nterstate commerce commission today\ni. granted the application of the South\nern railway and Its connections to\nestablish a minimum carload weight\ni of 34,000 pounds on lumber from\nI point* iK VWiftWIa. North Carolina,\nSouth Carolina, Georgia and Tennes\nsee to Alexandria, Potomac Varda\nCharlottesville. Danville, Richmond.\nRoanoke (proper and for beyond),:\nEmporia, Franklin, Front Royal.\nRiverton, Suffolk. Strasburgr, Harris\n1 onburg. Lynchburg, Alta Vista (for\n1 beyond), Norfolk, Petersburg, Pin\nners Point, Portsmouth, West Nor\nfolk. West Point, South Richmond,\nMeherrln (for beyond), Va.. Wash\nington, Hagerstown, Md\u201e Shenandoah\nJunction, W. Va., Orange, Newport\nNews. Hampton, Va.. and Southern\nrailway stations on the Washington\ndivision between Alexandria and\nLynchburg, Va, Including Harrison\nburg branch, and Washington and\nOld Dominion railway stations.\nHeretofore there has been a dif\nference In minimum weights and now\nthe carriers will be permitted to\n1 put into effect the uniform minimum\ncarload weight.\nThis is. In effect, an fncrease In\nI lumber rates to Virginia Shipper*,\nas shipments under 34,000 pounds,\n(carload, will be compelled to pay the\nless-than-carioad rate, which Is high\ner than the carload rate. These rates\nKill continue pending \u00abo In*\ntlan by the commission.\nThe commission also granted the\napplication of the Southern railway\nand lta connection* to eetabllah\nio\u00bb>\u2014walnut. cherry and cedar\u2014\ncarloads. weights 34,606 pounds front\npoints in Virginia. North Carolina.\nKentucky, Georgia and Tenneaaee. to\nEastern and Virginia cttleg. interior\nEastern, New England and Caaddthg\npoints, and Pittsburg-Buffalo terri\ntory, the same as now In effect oa\nlumber\u2014walnut, cherry and cedar.\nThis Is a material benefit to Vir\nginia lumber dealers, as the\nrate on lumber Is lower than cm\nwhich Is to be reduced.\nSENT TO GRAND JURY\nFROM POLICE COURT\nA w. Thompson, arraigned in foMo*\ncourt yesterday on charge of murder*\nIng J. W. Rainey, December 36th, who\ndied. It is alleged as the result of\nboating given by Thompson, was ballad\nin the sum of $3,666 to await the aetisn\nof the grand Jury. Security was given\nby Bam Cohen.\nEdward Popp, alts* William* color\ned. was held for tho grand Jury oa\ncharge of assaulting and wowntlaff\nAnrila 1 oh neon aaImoa^I\nMay the Memories of 1913\nI\nEver remain GREEN, and may 1914 be the RED(D)\nletter year of your existence.\nWe thank you most heartily for your flattering\npatronage.\nGREEN REED\n1 -..V. ...V\nr.'-.-ki. I -v '\u2022Pi. AiJMEB","height":"27968","width":"20472"}}
